   As always you have made a good point. Perhaps a 'clean' nuke is a contradiction in terms. I think part of the 'cleanness' of the Davy Crocket is to be found in the fact that the plutonium core is so small. Be that as it may I certainly wouldn't want to take my girl friend on a picnic at ground zero of a fresh Davy Crocket surface test blast.<br>
   I am not a proponent of a nuclear lift off for Orion. A cluster of 16 Shuttle solid boosters would provide 24,400 tons of thrust and be capable of boosting a 4000 ton Orion to a safe altitude of about 30 miles before the first nuke is kicked out the back and detonated. <br>
   On the other hand the exhaust gasses from the Space shuttles SRB’s are about as toxic as poison gas and do create considerable atmospheric pollution. Every time the Space shuttle punches its way into orbit it spits out 1100 tons of toxic waste into the air. I wonder if anyone has ever done a study of how many people have died as a result of all the pollution caused by  Space shuttle launches. As you know statistics can be made to support or attack just about any view. <br>
<br>
I say build the damn thing (Orion) and kick it into orbit and get on with the business of manned exploration of the Solar system. <br>
