<br>
That’s a tough one since Earth’s magnetic field extends to about 38,000 miles on the side facing the sun and about 185,000 miles on the side opposite the sun. That means that our 4000 ton Orion would need to be kicked up to a velocity of about 20,000 mph with chemical engines to get to a completely safe altitude before we can start nuking our way to the outer planets.<br>
<br>
Just how big would the booster need to me to accomplish this task using liquid oxygen and diatomic hydrogen as fuel? Well to put a 4000 ton Orion into that position it would take about 60,000 - 70,000 tons of fuel tanks, propellant, motors, and structures. OUCH!<br>
<br>
Regardless of the ‘statistical deaths’ that might result from a launch inside the Earth’s atmosphere the only real options are to go for it or forget it. Scaled down versions of Orion with tiny pusher plates like the one that was supposed to be placed into orbit by a single Saturn V launch Have ISP’s that barley exceed 1000 and hence are not much better than NERVA. As they say the Idea scales up better than it scales down.<br>
<br>
 Realistically speaking  the Soviets and the United States conducted over a thousand above ground nuclear tests and I don’t seem to recall the end of the life on Earth as we know it. We sullied the planet in the name of national defense so I think that we can justifiably add a little bit more filth in the name of large scale human expansion into the solar system. Of course the nutless tree huggers will never buy it.<br>
<br>
NukePulse<br>
